03965nam a22005535i 9780691258898DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20231992nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912588987 a10.1515/97806912588982doi  a(DE-B1597)677684  a(OCoLC)1414455582  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aLIT0041202bisacsh04a792/09141 aStraub, Kristina, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSexual Suspects :bEighteenth-Century Players and Sexual Ideology /cKristina Straub. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2023] 4c©1992  a1 online resource (212 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tI. Ocular Affairs: The Gendering of Eighteenth-Century Spectacle -- tII. Colley Cibber’s Butt: The Construction of Actors’ Masculinity -- tIII. Colley Cibber’s Fops: Actors and Homophobia -- tIV. Men from Boys: Cibber, Pope, and the Schoolboy -- tV. The Construction of Actresses’ Femininity -- tVI. George Anne Bellamy: The Actress as Sentimental Victim -- tVII. The Guilty Pleasures of Female Theatrical Cross-Dressing and the Autobiography of Charlotte Charke -- tVIII. Bodies in Pain: The Subjection of Players -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow the suspect sexuality of actors and actresses shaped early modern debates about gender and sexual identityFrom the Restoration through the eighteenth century, the sexuality of actors and actresses was written about in ways that stirred the public imagination. Actors were frequently suspected of heterosexual promiscuity or labeled effeminate or even as “sodomites,” and actresses were often viewed as prostitutes or sexually ambivalent victims of their profession. Kristina Straub argues that this depiction of players greatly shaped public debates about what made women feminine and men masculine. Considering a wide range of literature by or about players—pamphlets, newspaper reports, theatrical histories, and biographies as well as the public correspondence between Alexander Pope and the famed actor Colley Cibber—she examines the formation of gender roles and sexual identities during a period crucial to modern thinking on these issues.Drawing from feminist-materialist and gay and lesbian theories and historiographies, Sexual Suspects analyzes the complex development of spectacle and spectatorship as gendered concepts. She reveals how national, racial, and class differences contributed to the subjection of players as professional spectacles and how images of race, class, and gender combined to create divisions between “normal” and “deviant” sexuality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691258898?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691258898423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780691258898/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles